In the aftermath of the coup, Gorbachev fired his foreign minister and acting defense minister.
Boris Yeltsin fired the heads of the state-owned media.
The Moscow City Council ordered all Communist Party buildings in the capital sealed and telephone service cut off to party and KGB buildings.
Speaking before the Russian Parliament, Gorbachev affirmed Yeltsin's decrees issued during the coup as legitimate.
Yeltsin commented several times during Gorbachev's speech and Gorbachev deferred to him several times for details of happenings during his detention.
Six of the top party officials were arrested for instigating the coup. 
